otocol emphasizes that assessment begins with a multidisciplinary evaluation, integrating risk factors and initial presentation through structured clinical entities. 'Incidental finding of nodule,' whether suspicious for lung cancer or found in an asymptomatic patient, leads to further risk assessment and assignment to nodule type categories. These steps underscore the importance of a holistic, team-based approach, including radiologic and clinical expertise, to maximize diagnostic yield and efficiently triage patients. Relationship data further enforces that clinical and radiologic findings converge early in the process, streamlining subsequent pathway selection [Data: Entities (1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8); Relationships (0,4,5,7,8,9,10,11,13)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Protocols for Solid Versus Subsolid Nodules Are Systematically Delineated\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Using the branching structure from DIAG-1 based on nodule type, the pathway segregates into DIAG-2 (solid nodules) and DIAG-3 (subsolid nodules), each with distinct follow-up steps. For solid nodules, options include 'No routine follow-up' or, if stable, intervals for imaging at 18–24 months, or, in specific scenarios, aggressive evaluation with CT at 3 months, FDG-PET/CT, or biopsy. Subsolid nodule pathways are even more granular, differentiating solitary pure, part-solid, and multiple subsolid nodules with corresponding size thresholds and tailored imaging intervals. This encapsulates the protocol’s sophistication and adaptability to diverse clinical scenarios [Data: Entities (5,6,9,10,22,23,24,25); Relationships (16,23,25,26,43,51,52,53,54,59,62,65)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Clear Triggers for Advanced Diagnostics and Biopsy\",\n      \"explanation\": \"The protocol includes explicit recommendations for escalated diagnostics in specific cases—such as solid component ≥6 mm or certain changes at follow-up—triggering consideration of FDG-PET/CT or biopsy. This is evident both in D